Tutor role, profile calibration, and Skill routing are defined in
`tutor-core.mdc`. This rule holds the capture, recording, and project policies
until they are split into dedicated intelligent rules.

## Project calibration
If there is a `LEARNING-PROJECT`, use stack/candidates to calibrate what makes
sense in this repo. Project candidates are **not** the global queue — promote
them only when there is a real gap (conceptual question, `/study-probe`, or an
explicit request).

## Intent classification (required, before answering)
Classify the user message into one of the intents below. Do not announce the
classification unless I ask.

| Intent | Signals | Log action |
|---|---|---|
| `concept_gap` | “what is X?”, “how does X work?”, “difference between A and B?” **without** pointing at a repo file/module | Explain at the right level + **automatic `want`** for the main concept |
| `repo_local` | “what does module X do?”, “how was Y built?”, paths, codebase symbols | Answer from the code; **do not** log |
| `agent_task` | “do”, “implement”, “fix”, “refactor”, execution requests | Execute; log only if you taught a relevant new concept |
| `meta_learning` | `/study-*`, “add to queue”, “mark as covered” | Follow the command / request |

### Anti-noise for `concept_gap` (auto-want)
- At most **1** `want` per turn (the main concept).
- Do not log if it is already in the queue or recently covered (CLI dedupes/normalizes).
- Do not log bare generic terms: code, file, error, function, module…
- Do not log bare base languages (Python, JS, TypeScript…); frameworks, tools,
  and protocols are fine (Docker, HTTP, Prisma, CI, PR…).
- If X is only repo jargon with no transferable concept → treat as `repo_local`.

## When I bump into a new concept
Even if the main task is something else:
1. Explain at the right level, with one concrete example.
2. If it is `concept_gap`, save to the queue with the CLI (below) and confirm.
3. Recommend material only if the topic is new/fundamental OR if I ask.
   At most 1–2 specific sources (name + why it helps). Never “search for X”.
4. For a curated track, tell me to run `/study-deep` (do not research it yourself
   in chat).

## Project / stack context
In a repo with clear signals (`package.json`, `pyproject.toml`, `Dockerfile`,
`compose.yml`, `Cargo.toml`, README, etc.), if there is **no** useful
`LEARNING-PROJECT`, you may sync 3–8 specific candidates, without obvious
base languages:

```bash
python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py project-sync --stack "A;B" --candidates "topic1;topic2;topic3"
```

Do not sync every turn — only at a useful start of project work, during
`/study-probe`, or if I ask.

## How to record (simple and reliable)
Two ways. Prefer the CLI when possible.

### A) CLI (preferred — works even if the hook fails)
```bash
python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py covered --topic "TOPIC" --level "beginner|intermediate|advanced" --note "context"
python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py want --topic "TOPIC" --note "why I want it"
python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py init --level "intermediate" --focus "area"
python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py project-show
python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py project-sync --stack "..." --candidates "a;b"
python3 ~/.cursor/learning/cli.py project-drop --topic "TOPIC"
```
If `~/.cursor/learning/cli.py` does not exist, say the plugin needs a new
chat/session (`sessionStart` installs the CLI) or run `/study-log`.

### B) Marker (backup for the afterAgentResponse hook)
Isolated line at the end of the reply:
```
<!-- LEARNING-LOG topic="TOPIC" level="intermediate" note="context" -->
<!-- LEARNING-WANT topic="TOPIC" note="context" -->
```

### When to record
- `concept_gap` → `want` (or LEARNING-WANT), **automatically**.
- A relevant concept was just taught mid-task → `covered` and/or `want` if I
  want to go deeper later.
- I say I want to study X / leave it for later → `want`.
- `repo_local` / purely operational reply / plugin meta → **do not** record.

### Required feedback
If you saved something, say in one line: `Saved to profile: …` or `Saved to queue: …`.
If the CLI replied “Already in queue” / “Ignored”, no need to insist.
